[Black "Exchange Variation - Sideline"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C68"]
[Annotator "GM Michael Roiz"]
[PlyCount "36"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 {This position was first seen more than
150 years ago. Indeed, what can be more natural than damaging the opponent's
pawn structure and gain a tempo for developing pieces? However, as was proved
in dozens of games, the powerful bishops provide Black with full compensation
for doubled pawns in many lines of Exchange Ruy Lopez.} dxc6 5. Nc3 {White
develops the knight and attacks the e5-pawn. Among the merits of this move is
also the potential possibility of queenside castle. On the flipside, locking
the c-pawn diminishes White's control of d4.} (5. Nxe5 $6 {is known to be
dubious for any chess player since his childhood} Qd4 6. Nf3 Qxe4+ 7. Qe2 Qxe2+
8. Kxe2 Bg4 {Black was better in Hellbach-Chigorin,M St Petersburg 1900}) ({
Definitely cannot be recommended} 5. b3 $6 f6 6. Bb2 c5 $1 {Black seizes a lot
of space and makes d3-d4 impossible. Now White's setup looks rather passive.}
7. Qe2 Be6 8. O-O Bd6 9. c3 Ne7 10. d4 cxd4 11. cxd4 {This was Schultz
Pedersen,J - Hansen,L Copenhagen 2000 Now the natural} Ng6 $146 12. Nbd2 O-O
$15 {would have offered Black a better position.}) (5. d3 {This modest move
can be found in the practice of GM Rozentalis who is one of the most
experienced players in the Exchange Variation. Still, by deviating from
opening the position, White gives up the fight for the initiative.} Bd6 6. Be3
({Equally harmless is} 6. Nbd2 Ne7 7. Nc4 Ng6 8. a4 h6 9. d4 Bg4 10. dxe5 Nxe5
11. Ncxe5 Bxe5 {Rozentalis,E - Radulski,J Kallithea 2009}) 6... Ne7 7. Nbd2 c5
8. Nc4 f6 9. a4 Be6 10. O-O O-O 11. c3 Nc6 {Black was fine in Rozentalis, E -
Kuljasevic, D Trieste 2013}) (5. d4 {By this early advance White aims to fix a
favourable pawn structure, but the open character of play definitely suits
Black, whose bishops are getting powerful. Still, this was tried by many
strong players such as Adams, Karpov, Jobava and more, so it has to be covered.
} exd4 6. Qxd4 Qxd4 7. Nxd4 Bd6 {I like this flexible way of development, that
perfectly fits with our repertoire in the main lines. As usual, the knight is
going to be hosted on e7, so f7-f5 might follow at any moment.} (7... c5 $5 8.
Ne2 Bd7 9. Nbc3 O-O-O {seems viable either.}) 8. Nc3 (8. Be3 Ne7 9. Nd2 c5 10.
N4b3 b6 11. Nc4 Be6 12. Nxd6+ cxd6 13. O-O-O O-O-O 14. f3 d5 {was slightly
better for Black in Ivanov,P -Nagibin,G Moscow 2006}) 8... Ne7 9. Be3 Bd7 $5 {
This is the most ambitious choice.} (9... f5 10. f3 O-O 11. O-O-O c5 {led to
equality in Speijer,A-Teichmann,R Hamburg 1910}) 10. O-O-O O-O-O 11. Nb3 {
As usual, the knight is heading on c5.} (11. f3 Ng6 12. Nde2 Rhe8 13. Bf2 {
, as in Rodi, L - Perdomo,L Salvador 2011 can be well met by} h5 $5 14. Bg3 Bc5
15. h4 Be6 {White's kingside play is limited, so Black might consider some
active actions on the opposite side.}) ({The over-aggressive} 11. f4 f6 12. Nb3
Rhe8 13. Rde1 b6 $15 {put White under strong pressure in Motylev,A - Pavlidis,
A Legnica 2013}) 11... Ng6 12. Nc5 Be8 $1 {It makes sense to keep the
light-squared bishop on the board, while the temporary lack of connection
between the rooks doesn't bother Black.} 13. Nd3 b6 14. f4 ({The modest} 14. f3
f6 15. h4 h5 16. Ne2 c5 {also offered Black excellent play in John, W-Euwe, M
Gothenburg 1920}) 14... f6 15. g3 c5 16. f5 {The natural play from both sides
led to this position in Dorin, M - Sorin, A Pena City 1996 Now the natural} Ne5
$146 17. Bf4 Bh5 18. Rd2 Nxd3+ 19. cxd3 ({Hardly better is} 19. Rxd3 c4 20. Rd5
Bc5 $15) 19... Bxf4 20. gxf4 Bf7 {would have yielded Black some positional
advantage in view of the weak d3-pawn.}) 5... Bd6 (5... f6 {is the most common
alternative, but I find this way of handling the position to be as effective
as after 5.0-0}) 6. d4 {This is the only adequate response.} exd4 7. Qxd4 f6 8.
Be3 ({In case of} 8. O-O Ne7 9. e5 ({After} 9. Be3 Ng6 10. Nd2 Be6 11. f4 Bf7
12. Rad1 O-O 13. Nb3 Qe7 $15 {White's pawn centre was very vulnerable in Liu,
G - Mamedyarov,S Tbilisi GEO 2017}) 9... fxe5 10. Nxe5 Ng6 {White hardly
benefits from opening the e-file. For instance,} 11. Bf4 Qf6 12. Bg3 Bf5 13.
Ne4 $6 ({Better was} 13. Nf3 {, maintaining the balance.}) 13... Bxe4 14. Qxe4
Bxe5 15. Bxe5 Qxe5 16. Qxe5+ Nxe5 17. Rae1 O-O-O 18. Rxe5 Rd2 {Black has
better chances due to his control of the second rank in Solak, D - Antoniewski,
R Kallithea 2003}) 8... Ne7 9. O-O-O Ng6 {A similar approach can be seen in
the main line - Black takes control over e5, so the king can stay in the
centre for a while.} 10. Qc4 ({The ambitious} 10. h4 {, as was tried in a few
games, can be naturally met by} Bg4 $1 11. Qc4 Qe7 12. h5 Ne5 {with excellent
play.}) 10... Qe7 11. Nd4 {It looks like White managed to cover e6 and keep
opponent's king in the centre, but after} Qf7 {he has nothing better than
liquidating into the endgame} 12. Qxf7+ Kxf7 13. f3 h5 $1 {This a typical way
of limiting White's active possibilities on the kingside.} 14. Kb1 h4 15. h3 {
We have been following the game Hasangatin, R - Zavadil, M Marianske Lazne
2004 Now Black should have opted for} c5 $1 $146 16. Nde2 (16. Nf5 Bxf5 17.
exf5 Ne7 $15 {would drop the f5-pawn.}) 16... b5 17. Nd5 Ne5 18. b3 Bb7 {
White's pawns majority on the kingside is neutralized while Black's bishops
start dominating over the board.} *

