{[%evp 0,34,16,28,25,18,24,15,21,23,23,13,61,42,19,19,19,3,-2,29,40,27,28,28,
24,-19,30,-21,26,32,18,18,14,11,58,34,37]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4.
Bxc6 dxc6 5. O-O {Undoubtedly, the main continuation. At the moment, White has
both the better pawn structure and lead in development. Therefore, Black's
main task is completing the development and maintaining the bishops pair. In
such positions, the pair of bishops is usually a good compensation for the
damaged pawn structure.} Bd6 {This move is only Black's 4th choice, but it
looks most natural - why not defend the pawn and develop a minor piece? In
fact, it was first played in 1867, when chess was practically unexplored!} 6.
d4 {This is definitely the most challenging approach. Since the d-file is
locked, this move isn't connected with liquidating into an endgame.} (6. c3 {
It definitely makes sense to build up a strong pawn centre, but it yields
Black an important tempo for completing the development.} Ne7 (6... Bg4 {
was played in some high-level games, but I see no reason for exchanging the
powerful light-squared bishop.}) 7. d4 exd4 8. cxd4 (8. e5 $6 Bc5 9. cxd4 Bb6
$15 {leaves White with a weak pawn on d4.}) 8... Ng6 9. Nc3 {This position
occurred in Kreiter, T -Kreutzer, A Willingen 2005 Now my natural improvement
is} O-O $146 10. h3 ({In case of} 10. Be3 Bg4 11. h3 Bxf3 12. Qxf3 f5 $1 13. e5
f4 {Black manages to seize the initiative.}) 10... Be6 11. Qc2 f5 $1 12. Ng5
Qd7 13. Nxe6 Qxe6 14. e5 Bb4 $132 {Black, who took control over the light
squares, has a comfortable play.}) (6. Na3 {This somewhat artificial move was
successfully employed by such strong players like Baadur Jobava, Arkadiy
Naiditch and others. White's idea is obvious - quickly exchange one of Black's
bishops and then push d2-d4.} Be6 7. d4 ({Toothless is} 7. Qe2 {,as in Rausis,
I - Rasmussen, R Reykjavik 1998} Ne7 8. Nc4 Ng6 {, and Black is very
comfortable.}) 7... exd4 8. Qxd4 f6 9. Qc3 Ne7 10. Nd4 {Only this new move has
an independent value.} (10. Nc4 Bxc4 11. Qxc4 {transposes to 6.d4}) 10... Qd7 {
This time Black converts the bishop pair into better piece coordination.} 11.
Nxe6 Qxe6 12. Nc4 O-O-O ({The engine's recommendation} 12... Qxe4 13. Re1 Qg4 {
isn't in everyone's taste!}) 13. Nxd6+ ({Hardly stronger is} 13. f3 Bc5+ 14.
Be3 Bxe3+ 15. Nxe3 Ng6 16. b3 Nf4 $132) 13... Rxd6 14. Bf4 Rd7 15. f3 Ng6 16.
Bg3 Rhd8 $132 {The full control over d-file offers Black enough counter-play.})
6... exd4 7. Qxd4 {Again, the most aggressive - by attacking the g7-pawn,
White gains another tempo.} ({Another recapture is less challenging:} 7. Nxd4
Ne7 8. Be3 ({After} 8. Nc3 O-O {[%cal Gf7f5]} 9. Be3 f5 $1 {Black got the
upper hand in Obrusnik, D - Krzyzanowski, M Pszczyna 2007} 10. exf5 Nxf5 11.
Nxf5 Bxf5 {[%csl Rc2,Gd6,Gf5][%cal Gd8h4]}) 8... O-O 9. f4 {White's ambitious
play exposes the e4-pawn. So, at this point, I offer the following new way of
handling the position:} Re8 $1 $146 {[%csl Re4][%cal Ge7d5]} 10. Qd3 (10. Nc3
Nd5 $1 11. exd5 Rxe3 12. dxc6 Bc5 $36) 10... c5 11. Nf3 b5 {The lack of
light-squared bishop in White's camp starts to tell now} 12. Nc3 (12. e5 c4 13.
Qd2 Nf5 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Gc8b7]} 14. Nc3 Bb4 $15) 12... Bb7 13. e5 c4 14. Qe2
Bb4 15. Rad1 Qc8 $15) 7... f6 {Undoubtedly, the key position of 5...Bd6 line.
From now both player's plans are clear: White would try to attack the
d6-bishop with his knight and put pressure along the d-file while Black's main
task is completing the development and moving his king towards the queenside.}
8. Be3 {[%cal Gb1d2,Gd2c4]} ({Another way of attacking the bishop seems less
effective:} 8. b3 Ne7 9. Ba3 Bg4 10. Bxd6 Bxf3 11. Bc5 (11. gxf3 $6 Qxd6 12.
Qxd6 cxd6 $15 {leaves White with no compensation his for damaged pawn
structure on the kingside.}) 11... Qxd4 12. Bxd4 Rd8 13. Bc5 Bxe4 14. Re1 Rd7
15. Nc3 Bd5 {White had to fight for equality in Ivanchuk, V - Carlsen, M Wijk
aan Zee 2008}) ({The attempt to immediately make use of the development
advantage by means of} 8. e5 fxe5 9. Nxe5 {might favour Black, whose bishops
are getting very powerful. For instance,} Ne7 10. Bg5 Be6 11. Nc3 O-O 12. Rad1
{This position took place in Kagan, S - Rumens, D Hastings 1976} (12. Ne4 {
is well met by} Nf5 $1 13. Qc3 Qe8 {with a great play.}) ({The same can be
said about} 12. Rfe1 Nf5 $1 13. Qd2 Qe8 14. Rad1 h6 15. Bf4 Rd8 16. Qe2 {
This was Barczay, L - Honfi, K Kecskemet 1979 Now} c5 $1 $146 {, securing
d4-spot for the knight would have yielded Black an excellent position.}) {
Now it made sense to play} 12... Rf5 $146 13. Bf4 Nd5 14. Nxd5 Bxd5 15. Bg3 Qf6
{The bishops are so strong, that only White might face problems in this
position.}) (8. Nc3 Ne7 {is covered in 5.Nc3 Chapter}) (8. Re1 {is almost the
same as 8.e5 and doesn't offer White any advantage:} Ne7 9. e5 fxe5 10. Nxe5
O-O 11. Bg5 Be6 12. Qe4 Bd5 13. Qg4 Qc8 $11 {Negi,P - Lenic,L New Delhi 2011})
({Harmless is also} 8. c4 c5 9. Qd5 Ne7 10. Qh5+ Ng6 11. Nh4 Be6 $1 12. Nxg6
Bf7 13. Qh4 Bxg6 {Black regained the piece in a favourable situation in
Navarro Cia,M - Hebden,M England ENG 2018}) ({and} 8. Qc4 Ne7 9. Qb3 Qd7 10.
Re1 Ng6 11. Be3 Qf7 {Black successfully solved his problems in Oleksienko, M -
Igonin, T Abu Dhabi 2016}) (8. Nbd2 {This is White's second choice. The knight
temporarily locks the bishop, but it goes to c4 at once.} Be6 9. b3 {The most
logical - the knight can be hosted on c4, while the dark-squared bishop gets
excellent prospects.} ({The alternatives are less promising:} 9. Nb3 {White
provokes the somewhat weakening b7-b6, but the b3-knight is clearly misplaced.}
b6 10. e5 fxe5 11. Nxe5 Ne7 12. Bg5 O-O 13. Rfe1 {Visually, the location of
Black's minor pieces are unstable. However, after} Qe8 14. Nc4 Nf5 {he
successfully releases the tension} 15. Nxd6 cxd6 16. Qxb6 ({After} 16. Qe4 Bd5
17. Qxe8 Raxe8 {Black was slightly better due to the powerful d5-bishop in
Kupreichik, V - Pytel, K Dortmund 1975}) 16... Qg6 17. Bf4 Bd5 18. Bg3 Nxg3 19.
hxg3 Qxc2 {White has to play accurately in order to maintain the balance.}) ({
Again,} 9. Nc4 $2 Bxh2+ {drops the pawn.}) (9. Qc3 Ne7 10. Nc4 ({I've examined
also} 10. Nd4 $146 Qd7 11. Nxe6 Qxe6 12. Nc4 O-O-O 13. Nxd6+ cxd6 14. Re1 d5 $1
{In the endgame, that arises after} 15. exd5 Nxd5 16. Rxe6 Nxc3 17. Bh6 gxh6
18. bxc3 Rd2 {the control of the second rank offers Black sufficient
counterplay.}) 10... Bxc4 11. Qxc4 Qd7 12. Be3 Ng6 13. Nd4 (13. Rad1 O-O-O 14.
Rfe1 Rhe8 15. Bc1 c5 16. b3 Qb5 $1 {was better for Black in Socko,B - Matlakov,
M Moscow 2016}) 13... O-O-O {transposes to 8.Be3}) 9... Ne7 10. Nc4 ({After} 
10. Bb2 Ng6 {White has nothing better than} 11. Nc4 Bxc4 12. Qxc4 {, and now
Black can at least play} Qd7 {, transposing to text.}) 10... Bxc4 {As usual,
Black prefers to keep his important dark-squared bishop on the board.} 11. Qxc4
Qd7 12. Bb2 (12. e5 fxe5 13. Bb2 Ng6 {might transpose to text.}) 12... Ng6 13.
e5 {This ambitious continuation only invites major simplifications.} ({In case
of} 13. Rad1 O-O-O 14. Nd4 Be5 {the pin along the d-file looks annoying.} 15.
Qe2 {This position was seen more than 100 years ago in Bernstein, O-Mykolaiv,B
Kyiv 1903 Black could have benefited from having better coordination between
the pieces after} Qf7 $1 16. Ba1 h5 17. Nf3 Bd6 {White's king is under
definite pressure.}) 13... fxe5 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. Bxe5 Bxe5 16. Rae1 O-O-O 17.
Rxe5 Rhe8 {The activity of Black's rooks fully compensated for the inferior
pawn structure in Gaponenko, I - Muzychuk, A Doha 2016.}) 8... Ne7 9. Nbd2 Be6
$1 {This developing move has a tactical point.} 10. Qc3 {The most common.
White insists on Nd2-c4 and vacates the d4-square for another knight. Also,
the opposition of rook and opponent's queen might be promising in the long run.
} ({The other natural continuation is} 10. Rad1 Ng6 11. Nc4 Bxc4 {[%csl Gd6]
[%cal Ge8c8] Of course, the Bd6 is much more important for Black, since it
locks the d-file and makes the queenside castling possible.} 12. Qxc4 Qe7 {
[%csl Ga6,Gb7,Gc6,Gc7][%cal Ge8c8] It turns out, that even though Black was
forced to exchange his bishop, there is still plenty of counterplay along the
e-file.} 13. Rd3 ({The attempt to develop an attack on the queenside takes too
much time:} 13. c3 {[%cal Gb2b4,Ga2a4,Gb4b5]} O-O-O 14. b4 Rhe8 15. Rd4 {
A sad necessity - this awkward move is the only way to cover the e4-pawn.} Qe6
16. Qxe6+ Rxe6 17. Nd2 Ne5 {[%cal Ge5g4]} 18. f3 Rde8 {[%cal Gc6c5]} 19. Nb3 f5
$1 20. Bf2 fxe4 21. Rxe4 Nd3 {[%cal Gc6c5] Black took over the initiative in
Novikov,S - Tomashevsky,E St Petersburg RUS 2018}) (13. Rfe1 O-O-O 14. a4 (14.
Bd4 Rhe8 15. Bc3 c5 16. a4 Qe6 17. Qxe6+ Rxe6 {might lead to the same.}) 14...
Rhe8 15. Bd4 Qe6 16. Qxe6+ Rxe6 17. Bc3 c5 18. g3 Rde8 19. Nd2 b5 {1/2 (61)
Machotka,J-Hagberg,J ICCF email 2010}) 13... O-O-O 14. Re1 Rhe8 15. Bc1 c5 {
White's setup looked too passive, so he couldn't pretend on claiming
superiority in Vachier Lagrave, M - Roiz, M Biel 2012}) ({The timid} 10. Nc4 $2
{runs into} Bxh2+ 11. Kxh2 Qxd4 12. Nxd4 Bxc4 $17 {, and Black is a pawn up.})
(10. Rfd1 Ng6 11. Nc4 Bxc4 12. Qxc4 Qe7 {was seen in many grandmaster games,
but in this case White faces even more problems with defending e4, whereas the
aggressive} 13. b4 O-O-O 14. a4 Bxb4 15. Rdb1 a5 16. c3 Bd6 17. Qb3 {, as was
played in few correspondence games, can be strongly met by} Kd7 $1 $146 18.
Qxb7 Rb8 19. Qa6 (19. Qxb8 Rxb8 20. Rxb8 Qxe4 $17) 19... Rxb1+ 20. Rxb1 Qxe4 {
, and White doesn't have any compensation for the pawn.}) 10... Qd7 $1 {
The most flexible. It makes sense to keep the knight one e7 for a while.} ({
Less precise is} 10... Ng6 11. Nd4 Qe7 12. a3 $1 O-O-O 13. f4 Bd7 14. b4 Rhe8
15. Kh1 $14 {Black's counterplay was heavily limited in Skripko,P - Klaus ICCF
email 2010}) 11. Rad1 ({White achieves no advantage with} 11. Nd4 Bf7 (11...
O-O-O $5 12. Nxe6 Qxe6 13. Qb3 Qxb3 14. axb3 f5 {, as in Radjabov,T - Aronian,
L Sochi 2006 also seems to suffice for equality, but the text looks ambitious.}
) 12. Nc4 c5 13. Nxd6+ ({In case of} 13. Ne2 Bxc4 14. Qxc4 Qb5 $1 15. Qxb5+
axb5 {the unusual pawn structure on the queenside favours Black, who can put
pressure along the a-file now.}) 13... cxd6 14. Ne2 Qc6 15. Rad1 O-O {Black
managed to complete the development and improve his pawn structure, so his
position isn't worse. Himanshu,S - Rajesh,V Dieren NED 2018}) ({Also after} 11.
Nc4 Bxc4 12. Qxc4 O-O-O 13. Nd4 Ng6 14. Nf5 Bf4 15. Bxf4 Nxf4 {The activity of
Black's pieces fully compensated for the inferior pawn structure in
Berelowitsch,A -Piorun,K Germany 2016}) 11... O-O-O 12. Nd4 ({White achieves
nothing with} 12. Nb3 $146 Ng6 13. Nc5 Qe7 {, and the black king is still safe,
whereas the e4-pawn is in danger.}) 12... Ng6 13. f3 Rhe8 14. Nxe6 Qxe6 {
White managed to comfortably cover the e4-pawn and exchange the opponent's
bishop. At the same time, Black's heavy pieces are still more active.} 15. Nc4
Bf4 16. a4 b6 17. b3 c5 {This was correspondence game Van Willigen, J - Hacker,
C ICCF email 2013. The chances are mutual.} *

