Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. Bxc6 {Losing a tempo looks absurd, but White is
trying to claim the drawbacks of placing the knight on f6. Indeed, in some
cases, the e5-pawn cannot be covered by f7-f6. Still, one tempo means a lot in
Ruy Lopez.} (5. d4 {A gambit line, that was especially common in the middle of
19th century. It was played by such great players of that time as Morphy and
Andersen.} exd4 6. O-O ({In case of} 6. e5 {[%csl Ra4]} Ne4 {[%csl Ra4][%cal
Ge4c5]} 7. O-O {Black can force the favourable exchange of light-squared
bishop by means of} Nc5 $1 8. Bxc6 dxc6 9. Nxd4 Ne6 10. Nxe6 Bxe6 11. Qe2 (11.
Qxd8+ Rxd8 12. Nc3 Bf5 {[%csl Rc2]}) 11... Qh4 $15 {Pon,N -Saptarshi,R Nagpur
2008}) 6... Be7 ({Of course, Black shouldn't be too ''greedy'':} 6... Nxe4 $2
7. Re1 d5 8. Nxd4 {invites serious trouble.}) 7. e5 (7. Re1 b5 8. Bb3 ({
Also after} 8. e5 Nxe5 9. Nxe5 ({Sometimes White prefers to recapture with a
rook, keeping in mind the following knight's route:} 9. Rxe5 bxa4 10. Nxd4 O-O
11. Nf5 {Indeed, the f5-knight looks nice, but the other pieces are
undeveloped, so after} Re8 12. Bg5 d6 13. Nxe7+ Rxe7 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Rxe7
Qxe7 16. Nc3 Bb7 {Black managed to seize the initiative in Kotsur, P -
Jumabayev, R Astana 2012}) 9... bxa4 10. Qxd4 O-O {White manages to regain the
pawn, but the light-squared bishop offers Black an excellent play in all cases:
} 11. Qxa4 ({Or} 11. Bg5 Rb8 12. Nd2 h6 13. Bh4 Rb4 14. c4 c5 15. Qc3 Re8 $15 {
Plat,V - Percivaldi,M Newcastle ENG 2018}) 11... Rb8 12. Nc3 Rb4 13. Qa5 Bb7
$15 {was proved to be shaky for White in many games.}) 8... d6 {This position
might often arise also after 5.0-0. The major practical tests prove that White
has to struggle for equality here.} 9. Bd5 {The most common. White provokes
Black to open the e-file.} (9. Nxd4 $2 {is one of so-called ''kid traps'':}
Nxd4 10. Qxd4 c5 11. Qd1 c4 $19 {, and the bishop is gone.}) ({Ineffective is
also} 9. a4 Bg4 10. axb5 axb5 11. Rxa8 Qxa8 12. Na3 Qa5 $15 {Volokitin,A -
Dorfman,J Bad Wiessee 2001}) ({Or} 9. c3 dxc3 10. Nxc3 O-O 11. Nd5 Bg4 12. Bf4
Ne5 $15 {White is left without adequate compensation for the pawn in
Hangweyrer, M - Franzen, J Austria 1995}) 9... Nxd5 10. exd5 Ne5 11. Nxd4 (11.
Nxe5 $2 dxe5 12. Rxe5 O-O 13. Qxd4 Bf6 {is just lost for White.}) 11... O-O {
Visually, White's position doesn't look so bad: he regained the pawn, while
his knight potentially can be hosted on c6. However, the vulnerability of d5
and the lack of light-squared bishop are the most important factors here.} 12.
a4 ({Hardly better is} 12. Nc3 Re8 13. Bf4 Bb7 $1 14. Bxe5 dxe5 15. Rxe5 b4 16.
Ne4 Bf8 17. Rxe8 Qxe8 18. Qd3 Bxd5 {Black's powerful bishops put White in
serious danger in the correspondence game Gutovskyi, M - Roubaud, D 2010})
12... Bg4 $1 {It is vital to provoke f2-f3 before putting the bishop on d7} 13.
f3 Bd7 14. Nc3 b4 15. Ne4 f5 16. Nf2 Bf6 $15 {White was doomed to passive
defence in Havelka, J - Hofirek, B Kouty nad Desnou 2013}) 7... Ne4 8. Nxd4 (8.
Re1 Nc5 9. Bxc6 dxc6 10. Nxd4 Ne6 11. Nf5 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 Bd8 {In comparison to
the Berlin, Black can easily connect the rooks and quickly remove his king
from the centre.} 13. Nc3 O-O 14. Ne4 b6 15. Nfg3 c5 16. Be3 Bb7 17. f4 {
We have been following the classical game Richter, K-Bogoljubow, E Berlin 1928
At this moment, Black should have played} Re8 $1 $146 18. Rd2 h5 $15 {, and
the vulnerability of light squares in White's camp starts to tell.}) 8... O-O
9. Nf5 {[%csl Ra1,Rb1,Rc1] The presence of the f5-knight mostly increases
White's attacking potential, but here it costs too much time.} d5 10. Nxe7+ ({
Black definitely can do with the damage of his pawn structure after} 10. Bxc6
bxc6 11. Nxe7+ Qxe7 12. Re1 Re8 13. f3 Nc5 14. b3 Ne6 15. Qd2 Qc5+ 16. Qf2 Qd4
{Black was much more active and eventually won in Gashimov, V - Ivanchuk, V
Antalya 2004}) 10... Nxe7 11. c3 Nc5 12. Bc2 Bf5 13. Na3 Qd7 14. Be3 Ne6 {
Zelcic,R -Plenca,J Zagreb CRO 2018}) 5... dxc6 6. d3 Bd6 (6... Nd7 {is another
common move, but the text looks more natural - why should Black lock his
light-squared bishop instead of developing a piece?}) 7. Nbd2 (7. Bg5 {the pin
doesn't bother Black at all. Moreover, mostly the bishop is sort of stuck on
h4 or g3. For instance,} h6 8. Bh4 Qe7 9. Nbd2 Be6 10. Qe2 O-O-O 11. Bg3 Nd7
$15 {White was suffering from lack of space in Graf, P - Grabarczyk,M Police
2010}) 7... Be6 8. b3 Nd7 9. Bb2 Qe7 10. d4 {White hardly has any other
constructive plan.} ({After} 10. Nc4 f6 11. Nh4 g6 12. g3 Bc5 13. Qe2 b5 14.
Ne3 a5 {White was doomed to passive defence in Malakhov, I - Kovalev,V Minsk
2015}) 10... f6 11. Qe2 O-O-O 12. O-O-O {Dorfman, J - Mikhalchishin, A Tallinn
1988 At this moment I mostly like the prophylactic} Bf7 $146 13. dxe5 Nxe5 14.
Nxe5 Bxe5 15. Qe3 b6 16. f4 Bxb2+ 17. Kxb2 Rhe8 {The strong pressure on the e4
offers Black a comfortable play.} *

