1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d4 {A gambit line that was
especially common in the middle of the 19th century. It was played by such
great players of that time as Morphy and Andersen.} exd4 6. O-O ({In case of} 
6. e5 {[%csl Ra4]} Ne4 {[%csl Ra4][%cal Ge4c5]} 7. O-O {Black can force the
favourable exchange of light-squared bishops by means of} Nc5 $1 8. Bxc6 dxc6
9. Nxd4 Ne6 10. Nxe6 Bxe6 11. Qe2 (11. Qxd8+ Rxd8 12. Nc3 Bf5 {[%csl Rc2]})
11... Qh4 $15 {Pon,N -Saptarshi,R Nagpur 2008}) 6... Be7 ({Of course, Black
shouldn't be too ''greedy'':} 6... Nxe4 $2 7. Re1 d5 8. Nxd4 {invites serious
trouble.}) 7. e5 (7. Re1 b5 8. Bb3 ({Also after} 8. e5 Nxe5 9. Nxe5 ({
Sometimes White prefers to recapture with a rook, keeping in mind the
following knight's route:} 9. Rxe5 bxa4 10. Nxd4 O-O 11. Nf5 {Indeed, the Nf5
looks nice, but the other pieces are undeveloped, so after} Re8 12. Bg5 d6 13.
Nxe7+ Rxe7 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Rxe7 Qxe7 16. Nc3 Bb7 {Black managed to seize the
initiative in Kotsur, P - Jumabayev, R Astana 2012}) 9... bxa4 10. Qxd4 O-O {
White manages to regain the pawn, but the unopposed light-squared bishop
offers Black an excellent play in all cases:} 11. Qxa4 ({Or} 11. Bg5 Rb8 12.
Nd2 h6 13. Bh4 Rb4 14. c4 c5 15. Qc3 Re8 $15 {Plat,V - Percivaldi,M Newcastle
ENG 2018}) 11... Rb8 12. Nc3 Rb4 13. Qa5 Bb7 $15 {proved to be shaky for White
in many games.}) 8... d6 {This position might often arise also after 5.0-0.
The major practical tests prove that White has to struggle for equality here.}
9. Bd5 {The most common. White provokes Black to open the e-file.} (9. Nxd4 $2
{is one of the so-called ''kid traps'':} Nxd4 10. Qxd4 c5 11. Qd1 c4 $19 {
, and the bishop is gone.}) ({Ineffective is also} 9. a4 Bg4 10. axb5 axb5 11.
Rxa8 Qxa8 12. Na3 Qa5 $15 {Volokitin,A - Dorfman,J Bad Wiessee 2001}) ({Or} 9.
c3 dxc3 10. Nxc3 O-O 11. Nd5 Bg4 12. Bf4 Ne5 $15 {White is left without
adequate compensation for a pawn in Hangweyrer, M - Franzen, J Austria 1995})
9... Nxd5 10. exd5 Ne5 11. Nxd4 (11. Nxe5 $2 dxe5 12. Rxe5 O-O 13. Qxd4 Bf6 {
is just lost for White.}) 11... O-O {Visually, White's position doesn't look
so bad: he regained the pawn, while his knight potentially can be hosted on c6.
However, the vulnerability of the d5 pawn and the lack of light-squared bishop
are the most important factors here.} 12. a4 ({Hardly better is} 12. Nc3 Re8
13. Bf4 Bb7 $1 14. Bxe5 dxe5 15. Rxe5 b4 16. Ne4 Bf8 17. Rxe8 Qxe8 18. Qd3 Bxd5
{Black's powerful bishops put White in serious danger in the correspondence
game Gutovskyi, M - Roubaud, D 2010}) 12... Bg4 $1 {It is vital to provoke
f2-f3 before putting the bishop on d7} 13. f3 Bd7 14. Nc3 b4 15. Ne4 f5 16. Nf2
Bf6 $15 {White was doomed to passive defence in Havelka, J - Hofirek, B Kouty
nad Desnou 2013}) 7... Ne4 8. Nxd4 (8. Re1 Nc5 9. Bxc6 dxc6 10. Nxd4 Ne6 11.
Nf5 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 Bd8 {In comparison to Berlin, Black can easily connect the
rooks and quickly remove his king from the centre.} 13. Nc3 O-O 14. Ne4 b6 15.
Nfg3 c5 16. Be3 Bb7 17. f4 {We have been following the classical game Richter,
K-Bogoljubow, E Berlin 1928 At this moment Black should have played} Re8 $1
$146 18. Rd2 h5 $15 {, and the vulnerability of the light squares in White's
camp starts to tell.}) 8... O-O 9. Nf5 {[%csl Ra1,Rb1,Rc1] The presence of the
Nf5 mostly increases White's attacking potential, but here it cost too much
time.} d5 10. Nxe7+ ({Black definitely can do with damage of his pawn
structure after} 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. Nxe7+ Qxe7 12. Re1 Re8 13. f3 Nc5 14. b3 Ne6
15. Qd2 Qc5+ 16. Qf2 Qd4 {Black was much more active and eventually won in
Gashimov, V - Ivanchuk, V Antalya 2004}) 10... Nxe7 11. c3 Nc5 12. Bc2 Bf5 13.
Na3 Qd7 14. Be3 Ne6 {With a comfortable position for Black. Zelcic, R -Plenca,
J Zagreb CRO 2018} *

