{[%evp 0,30,28,23,23,20,13,13,13,-7,-7,-76,-21,-41,-44,-44,29,-70,2,-23,-16,
-16,10,-31,-39,-39,-39,-36,-34,-35,-9,-14,-9]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4.
Ba4 Nf6 5. Qe2 {This move is known since the middle of the 19th century and
was successfully employed by Howard Staunton. In comparison to 5.Nc3, White
keeps the possibility to build up a strong pawn centre with c2-c3 and d3-d4
while d1 is now vacant for the rook. However, this plan seems somewhat
artificial: By developing the queen White delays the development of his minor
pieces.} Be7 6. c3 {Only this move seems to have an independent value.} (6.
Bxc6 dxc6 7. O-O {is covered in 6.0-0 Be7 7.Bxc6} (7. b3 {An original idea:
White is trying to put more pressure on e5. Also, in some cases, he can place
the king on the queenside.} Nd7 8. Bb2 Bd6 9. d4 {The position opens in
Black's favour who's bishops are getting powerful.} ({The quiet} 9. d3 {
is hardly more promising:} O-O 10. Nbd2 Re8 11. h4 Nf8 12. Nc4 f6 13. h5 Ne6
14. g3 Bf8 $11 {Black managed to successfully regroup his pieces and take
control over d4-spot in Gurgenidze, B - Kaidanov, G Palma de Mallorca 1989})
9... exd4 10. Bxd4 O-O 11. Nbd2 Re8 12. O-O ({The more aggressive} 12. O-O-O $6
{is too risky:} a5 13. Nc4 Bf8 {, and Black has great attacking prospects on
the queenside.}) 12... Nc5 13. Rfe1 Bg4 {Black reached a comfortable position
in Gurgenidze, B - Dydyshko, V Moscow 1979})) (6. O-O b5 7. Bb3 O-O {
transposes to 7.Qe2}) 6... b5 7. Bb3 (7. Bc2 {This retreat looks rather
passive, but it was successfully employed by GM Sergei Tiviakov, one of
experts of 5.Qe2 line.} d5 $1 {There are no reasons for deviating from this
ambitious advance.} ({Instead,} 7... d6 8. d4 O-O 9. O-O Bg4 (9... exd4 10.
cxd4 Bg4 11. Rd1 Nb4 12. Bb3 $14) 10. d5 Na5 11. Nbd2 {looks somewhat passive
for Black.}) 8. d3 ({The more aggressive} 8. d4 {is well met by} Bg4 $1 9. exd5
Bxf3 10. Qxf3 Qxd5 11. Qxd5 Nxd5 12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. O-O O-O-O 14. Nd2 Bc5 {
Black's active piece play fully compensated for White's bishop pair in
Bisguier, A-Kashdan, I Baltimore 1948}) ({Too passive is} 8. exd5 Qxd5 (8...
Nxd5 $5 {was never played. It seems to offer Black full compensation for the
pawn:} 9. Nxe5 Nxe5 10. Qxe5 O-O 11. O-O Re8) 9. d3 O-O 10. O-O Bf5 11. Nbd2
Rfe8 12. Ne4 {Dalinger,H-Cervetto,M Villa Ballester 1998} h6 $146 13. Nfd2 Rad8
14. Nxf6+ Bxf6 15. Ne4 Be7 {Black has excellent play due to the pressure on d3.
}) 8... O-O 9. O-O Re8 {A flexible continuation. Black over-protects the
e5-pawn and makes f8 vacant for the bishop.} ({Another interesting option is} 
9... d4 10. Nbd2 Bg4 11. h3 Bh5 12. g4 Nxg4 13. hxg4 Bxg4 {Black has a
long-term compensation for the piece, but entering such complications isn't
everyone's taste.}) 10. Nbd2 ({It hardly makes any sense to leave the
b1-knight on its initial spot:} 10. Rd1 h6 11. Nbd2 Bd6 12. Nf1 Ne7 13. Ng3 Ng6
{Black reaches a harmonious setup and is ready to seize more space by
advancing the queenside pawns.}) 10... h6 11. Re1 Be6 $1 {The light-squared
bishop comes to overprotect the d5-pawn and makes Black's position more
flexible.} ({In comparison to abovementioned note,} 11... Bd6 {is now well met
by} 12. exd5 Nxd5 13. d4 $1 {, and White has great attacking prospects.}) 12.
h3 ({Harmless is also} 12. a4 Bf8 (12... Bd6 $5 {was possible too.}) 13. h3 {
This was Bakr Jwan, J - Sargissian, G Al Ain 2008 At this moment, it would
have made sense to connect the rooks with} Qd7 $146 {, since the Pe5 is
untouchable:} 14. exd5 Bxd5 15. axb5 axb5 16. Rxa8 Rxa8 $11 17. Nxe5 $4 Nxe5
18. Qxe5 Re8 $19) 12... Bd6 {Now Black's pawn centre is safe, so it's possible
to transfer the knight to g6} 13. Nf1 Ne7 14. d4 {This is the only adequate
way to fight for the initiative} (14. Ng3 Ng6 {is again very comfortable for
Black.}) 14... dxe4 15. Nxe5 c5 16. Ng3 cxd4 17. cxd4 Nf5 18. Nxf5 Bxf5 $11)
7... d5 $1 {This is the most energetic way to claim the drawbacks of White's
early queen sortie.} 8. d3 ({The over-optimistic} 8. d4 $6 exd4 9. e5 Ne4 10.
cxd4 Bg4 11. Be3 Bb4+ 12. Kf1 O-O $17 {left White with an awful pieces
coordination in Joseph, M - Denny, K Bridgetown 2012}) (8. exd5 Nxd5 9. Nxe5
Nxe5 10. Qxe5 Nf6 11. O-O (11. d4 O-O {changes nothing.}) 11... O-O 12. d4 Bd6
13. Qg5 ({Worse is} 13. Qe2 Re8 14. Qd3 c5 15. Bd1 {Wutz,C - Stoer,A Bayern
2011} Be6 $1 16. Nd2 Qd7 $17 {White fails to complete his development.}) 13...
Re8 {Black's lead in development fully compensates for the pawn, to say the
least.} 14. Na3 ({For instance,} 14. f3 c5 $1 15. Qh4 ({In case of} 15. Bf4
cxd4 16. cxd4 h6 17. Qh4 g5 18. Bxg5 hxg5 19. Qxg5+ Kh8 20. Bxf7 {White gets 4
pawns for a piece, but after} Rf8 21. Bb3 Ra7 $1 $40 {his king is under
massive attack!}) 15... Bf5 16. Bg5 c4 17. Bd1 Bd3 $17 {led White to material
losses in Mastrovasilis,D - Neelotpal,D Kavala 2012}) 14... h6 15. Qg6 Be6 {
Exchanging White's only active piece and connecting the heavy pieces.} 16. Qd3
Bxa3 17. bxa3 c5 18. Qd1 cxd4 19. cxd4 Bc4 $1 20. Bxc4 bxc4 $15 {Black took
the upper hand in Rodriguez, A - Sorin, A Salta 1995}) 8... O-O {Here we would
consider White's attempt to deviate from castling.} 9. Bg5 (9. O-O {This
position is covered in 7.Qe2.}) (9. Nbd2 Re8 10. Nf1 {This knight's route can
be seen in various lines of Ruy Lopez and Italian. However, this time White's
delay with castling might be punished by means of} a5 $1 $146 11. Ng3 (11. a4
b4 12. Ne3 bxc3 13. bxc3 d4 14. cxd4 Nxd4 15. Nxd4 Bb4+ 16. Bd2 Qxd4 $15) 11...
a4 12. Bc2 d4 13. O-O Be6 $15 {White suffers from a desperate lack of space.})
9... dxe4 10. dxe4 Nd7 $1 {This manoeuvre forces White to either retreat the
bishop or accept the unfavourable exchange.} 11. Be3 (11. Bxe7 Nxe7 12. O-O c5
{is also very comfortable for Black.}) 11... Na5 12. Bc2 Nc4 13. Bc1 Bb7 14.
Nbd2 Nxd2 15. Bxd2 c5 {Black has solved all his problems in Tiviakov, S -
Adams, M Groningen 1997} *

