1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Qe2 {Like after 5.Qe2,
White vacates d1 for his rook, so d2-d4 might follow soon. Moreover, there are
many possible transpositions into the lines covered after 5.Qe2. I have to
mention, that this modification is much more common on the high level and took
place in the practice of many top players including Anand, Ivanchuk, Svidler
and more.} b5 7. Bb3 O-O {The most flexible reply. Like after 5.Qe2, the pawn
sacrifice a-la Marschall is Black's main weapon, so there is no need to hurry
with d7-d6.} 8. c3 ({Attacking the pawn on b5 by means of} 8. a4 {isn't
effective in view of} Bb7 {, and now Black's development advantage should tell.
For instance,} 9. c3 ({Harmless is} 9. Nc3 Nd4 10. Nxd4 exd4 11. Nd5 Nxd5 12.
Bxd5 Bxd5 13. exd5 Rb8 $11) ({The modest} 9. d3 d6 10. c3 {fails to pose Black
any problems either:} Na5 11. Bc2 c5 12. Nbd2 Re8 13. Re1 Bf8 14. Nf1 {This
was Chistiakov, A-Lilienthal,A Moscow 1952 Now my natural suggestion is} h6
$146 15. Ng3 d5 {Black takes the upper hand.}) 9... d5 $1 {Again Marschall
stuff works perfectly!} 10. d3 ({Dubious is} 10. exd5 $6 Nxd5 11. axb5 Nf4 12.
Qd1 axb5 13. Rxa8 Qxa8 $15 {Gorbenko,V-Bolotov,A RCCA corr 2002}) 10... Na5 11.
Bc2 {We have been following the game Nechepurenko, R - Rej, T Yerevan 2006 At
this moment Black could have exploited the opponent's lack of development with}
b4 $146 12. cxb4 Nc6 13. Nc3 Nxb4 14. Nxe5 Bd6 {The activity of pieces
provides Black full compensation for the pawn, to say the least.}) ({The
aggressive} 8. d4 {was also seen a few times on the high level. Black should
play} Nxd4 $1 ({Instead,} 8... exd4 9. e5 Ne8 10. c3 dxc3 11. Nxc3 {offers
White interesting compensation for the pawn - the Ne8 is very poor.}) 9. Nxd4
exd4 10. e5 Ne8 11. c3 c5 $1 {It's not about keeping the extra pawn, but
mostly restricting White's knight} 12. cxd4 cxd4 13. Rd1 Qb6 14. Nd2 {If the
d4 pawn would fall, White would have the better pawn structure} Bb7 $146 {
This natural move is the simplest solution.} ({After} 14... Nc7 15. Ne4 Ne6 16.
Ng3 Re8 17. Nf5 Bf8 18. Qg4 {White had decent attacking prospects in Vallejo
Pons, F - Ding Liren Riyadh KSA 2017}) 15. Ne4 ({In case of} 15. Nf3 Nc7 16.
Nxd4 Qg6 17. Nf3 Rad8 {The pressure along the h1-a8 diagonal offers Black a
sufficient counter-play. For instance,} 18. Be3 d6 19. Bb6 Ne6 $1 $132 20. Bxd8
$140 Nf4 21. Qf1 Bxf3 $19) 15... d6 16. Bg5 {White is playing very
energetically, but he only manages to regain the material.} Bxg5 17. Nxg5 dxe5
18. Qxe5 Qf6 19. Qxf6 Nxf6 20. Rxd4 Rae8 $11) 8... d5 9. d3 ({After} 9. exd5
Nxd5 10. Nxe5 Nxe5 11. Qxe5 Nf6 12. d4 Bd6 {Black has enough play for a pawn,
as was mentioned in 5.Qe2 Chapter.}) 9... Re8 10. exd5 {In general, this
exchange leads to an unfavourable pawn structure. Therefore, it is usually
connected with some concrete idea - in particular, winning the e5 pawn. Even
though this move is relatively rare, I've decided to put as the main option.} (
10. Bg5 {This move almost forces Black to spot his bishop on e6, but there is
nothing wrong with that} Be6 11. Nbd2 h6 12. Bh4 (12. Bxf6 {looks toothless,
but it might invite interesting complications, as was seen in the following
correspondence game:} Bxf6 13. exd5 Bxd5 14. Ne4 Be7 15. c4 Be6 ({But not} 
15... bxc4 $6 16. dxc4 Be6 17. Ba4 $36) 16. cxb5 Bxb3 17. bxc6 Bd5 18. Nxe5 Bf8
{The vulnerability of White's knights yielded Black enough counter-play in
Coleman, P -Tiits, T ICCF email 2007}) 12... Nh5 $1 {A typical approach -
Black manages to release the tension and secure the d5 pawn.} 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14.
g3 Nf6 15. Rfe1 Rad8 {Black had nothing to worry about in Jovanovic, Z -
Bindrich, F Chur 2010}) ({The attempt to increase the pressure on the e5 pawn
is not effective:} 10. Re1 h6 11. Nbd2 {The knight moves towards g3, but it
takes a long time.} (11. exd5 {this looks like a concession since the d3 pawn
is getting weak whereas White's piece play isn't active enough} Nxd5 12. Nbd2 (
12. Nxe5 $2 Bf6 {, and White is in big trouble.}) 12... Be6 13. Ne4 Bf8 14. Bd2
Nb6 {Black's chances were preferable in Leenhouts, K - Bosch, J Netherlands
2003}) 11... Be6 12. Nf1 Qd7 13. Ng3 Bf8 14. Be3 {This position was reached in
Stevic, H - Arduman, C Istanbul 2003 Black's pieces are more active, and he
could have started the expansion on the queenside by means of} a5 $1 $146 15.
a4 ({Hardly better is} 15. exd5 Nxd5 16. d4 a4 17. Bc2 a3 $36) 15... b4 16. h3
Rab8 {would have put White in a passive position.}) (10. Rd1 {The opposition
of Rd1 and Black's queen visually looks promising, but White rarely manages to
make use of it} Be6 ({It is also possible to start with} 10... h6 11. Nbd2 Be6)
11. Nbd2 (11. Ng5 $6 Bg4 12. f3 Bh5 {leaves White with poor pieces
coordination.}) ({Harmless is also} 11. Bg5 Nh5 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13. g3 (13. exd5
Nf4 14. Qe4 f5 15. Qe1 Bxd5 $15) 13... Nf6 14. Nbd2 h6 {Torell,H - Durrett,R ,
internet 2013}) 11... h6 12. Nf1 Bd6 {I like this natural prophylactic move -
now the Nc6 isn't tied with covering the e5 pawn.} 13. Ng3 Na5 14. Bc2 c5 15.
Nh4 d4 {Black was better due to big space advantage in Varshini, V - Narayanan,
S Noida 2016}) (10. Nbd2 {Among White's possibilities, this seems most
flexible - there are no other prospects for White's knight anyways.} Bf8 ({
Dubious is now} 10... h6 $6 11. exd5 Nxd5 12. Nxe5 Nxe5 13. Qxe5 {, and the
compensation is questionable.}) 11. exd5 {This seems the most challenging.} ({
Most of the games saw} 11. Rd1 h6 12. Nf1 Na5 13. Bc2 c5 {, but then White's
position looks rather passive. For instance,} 14. h3 Nc6 15. Ng3 Be6 16. a4 Qc7
17. axb5 axb5 18. Rxa8 Rxa8 {Black took the upper hand in Massoni, M -Stigar,
P Budapest 2012}) ({Too slow seems} 11. a3 Be6 12. Ng5 Bg4 13. f3 {, as in
Stoinev, M - Karakehajov, K Sofia 2004 At this moment Black could have claimed
superiority with} Bc8 $146 14. exd5 Na5 15. Ba2 h6 16. Nge4 Nxd5 $15) 11... Na5
({Less precise is} 11... Nxd5 12. Ng5 $1 Qxg5 13. Bxd5 Bb7 14. Qf3 {, and
White's chances are preferable.}) 12. c4 $6 {An over-optimistic decision.
White underestimated his issues with development.} ({White should have played} 
12. Bc2 Nxd5 13. Re1 {, maintaining the balance.}) 12... bxc4 13. dxc4 e4 14.
Nd4 Bc5 15. Nc2 Ng4 {Black had a powerful initiative in Mortensen,E - Adams,M
Moscow 1994}) 10... Nxd5 11. Nxe5 ({I've also examined} 11. Ng5 $146 Bxg5 12.
Bxg5 f6 13. Be3 Be6 14. Nd2 a5 15. a4 b4 {Black has an excellent play.}) 11...
Nxe5 12. Qxe5 {Like in Marschall, if White would manage to consolidate and
keep the extra pawn, Black would be in trouble.} Be6 ({Weaker is} 12... Bb7 13.
Nd2 Qd7 14. Ne4 Rad8 15. Qg3 $14 {Vasiliev,O - Pogonina,N Porto Carras 2011})
13. Qg3 ({In case of} 13. d4 Bd6 14. Qh5 Qd7 15. Qf3 c6 16. h3 Bf5 $44) 13...
Bd6 14. Qf3 a5 $1 {An excellent resource that allows Black to pose White fresh
problems.} 15. Nd2 ({In case of} 15. a4 $146 b4 16. d4 Qd7 17. h3 c6 18. Nd2
Nf4 19. Bxe6 Qxe6 {Black has full compensation for a pawn due to control over
e-file.}) 15... a4 16. Bc2 {Releasing the pressure on the Nd5 is Black's
undisputable achievement.} Qd7 17. h3 {Covering g4.} f5 $1 {Black seizes more
space and restricts the mobility of White's pieces.} 18. Qd1 Bf7 19. Nf3 Bh5
20. a3 $2 {A waste of time.} (20. d4 {was better, but even then after} Bf4 $1
21. Kh1 Ra6 {Black has full compensation for a pawn.}) 20... Bf4 $1 {White got
under strong pressure and eventually lost in Strikovic,A - Sargissian,G Zafra
2007} *

