{[%evp 0,30,20,20,22,19,27,14,27,5,10,-10,35,-7,-3,-20,1,-51,-8,-6,12,12,9,0,
11,-15,6,-7,13,-16,-17,-7,6]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O
Be7 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. Qe1 {This is White's second choice according to the
statistics. In comparison to 7.Qe2, White is avoiding the unpleasant pin of
his knight. On the other hand, this move locks the f1-rook for a while, and
the location of White's queen is somewhat awkward itself.} (7. Qe2 {Quite a
rare move. The main idea behind it is making d1 vacant for the rook, so after
White pushes d2-d4 the opposition of Rd1 and Qd8 might be annoying for Black.
On the other hand, the delay with d2-d3 gives Black extra active ideas, since
the e4-pawn is still unsecured.} Bg4 $1 {This is the most convincing - finding
a good spot for the light-squared bishop is one of Black's main issues in such
positions.} 8. h3 Bh5 $1 {Again, the most challenging. It turns out that Black
is able to keep both his bishops on the board.} (8... Bxf3 {looks like a
definite concession. Let me show you one of my games in this line where White
managed to claim superiority:} 9. Qxf3 Nd7 10. d3 Nf8 (10... Bg5 11. Be3 Bxe3
12. Qxe3 O-O 13. Nd2 $14) 11. Qh5 (11. Qg3 $5) 11... Bf6 12. Be3 Ne6 13. Nd2
Qe7 14. Nc4 O-O 15. a3 $5 a5 $6 ({It was better to play} 15... c5) 16. a4 g6
17. Qg4 Bg7 18. Qg3 Qf6 19. Kh1 $14 {Black was doomed to passive defence till
the end of the game in Roiz, M - Hess, R Zuerich 2009}) 9. g4 ({Too passive is
} 9. d3 Nd7 10. Nbd2 f6 11. Nc4 Nc5 $15 {The e2-queen was clearly misplaced in
