{[%evp 0,30,30,28,23,23,23,20,13,-11,-7,-7,24,35,17,14,14,2,21,21,21,-3,12,13,
20,20,13,18,18,18,18,43,23]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. Nc3 {
This natural developing move was common 100-150 years ago and was successfully
employed by such great players of that time as Paulsen and Blackburne.
Nowadays, it is considered less flexible than 5.0-0, since it locks the c-pawn
and diminishes White's control of d4.} Be7 ({Another solid way of development
is} 5... Bc5) 6. O-O ({Once again, White can hardly benefit from damaging
Black's pawn structure after he gives up the powerful bishop:} 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7.
Nxe5 (7. d3 Nd7 8. Be3 O-O 9. O-O Re8 {Visually, White's pawn structure is
preferable. However, if he fails to push d3-d4 or f2-f4, there might be no
other constructive idea. At the same time, Black's task is clear: his knight
heads on d4.} 10. Qe2 ({The knight's transfer on g3 isn't very impressive
either:} 10. Ne2 Bf8 11. Ng3 c5 12. Nd2 g6 13. a4 Nb8 14. Nc4 Nc6 {Black
managed to successfully regroup his pieces and soon took the upper hand in
Durarbayli, V - Iordachescu, V Aix les Bains 2011}) 10... c5 11. a4 b6 12. Nd2
Nf8 13. Nc4 {We have been following the game Lagarde, M - Vitiugov, N Caleta
ENG 2019 At this moment, It would have made sense to cover e5 and leave the
e6-square vacant for the knight:} f6 $146 14. f4 exf4 15. Bxf4 Ne6 {Black's
chances are at least not worse.}) 7... Nxe4 $1 {As in the Exchange Variation,
Black can exploit the vulnerability of the opponent's knights and regain the
pawn.} 8. Nxe4 Qd5 9. O-O Qxe5 10. Re1 Be6 11. d3 Qd5 12. Bd2 O-O-O {This was
Dominguez Perez, L -Tomashevsky, E Huaian 2016 Black's position looks
preferable due to bishop pair.}) (6. d3 d6 7. a3 {This typical way of avoiding
the exchange of the light-squared bishop can be seen in various lines of Ruy
Lopez.} ({After} 7. Bxc6+ bxc6 8. d4 {This position resembles the Steinitz
system (4. ..d6 5.Bxc6+ bc 6.d4), but here Black's extra tempo makes it much
easier to reach equality.} exd4 9. Nxd4 (9. Qxd4) 9... Bd7 {As the tournament
practice proves, the bishop pair fully compensates for the structural
drawbacks here. For instance,} 10. O-O O-O 11. Qf3 {This is the most ambitious
choice - the knight can be hosted on f5 now.} ({Dubious is} 11. f4 $6 c5 12.
Nde2 Bc6 13. Ng3 Re8 $15 {Englisch,B-Mackenzie,G Paris 1878}) 11... Rb8 12. e5
({More to the point was} 12. b3 Re8 13. Bb2 Bf8 14. Rfe1 c5 15. Nf5 g6 16. Ng3
Bg7 {, but even so Black doesn't have any problems.}) 12... dxe5 13. Nxc6 Bxc6
14. Qxc6 Qd6 15. Qf3 Qe6 {Black had the more active play in Paichadze, L -
Giri, A Plovdiv 2012}) ({In case of} 7. O-O b5 8. Bb3 Na5 {Black manages to
liquidate the opponent's light-squared bishop in a favourable situation, so he
shouldn't face any problems. For instance,} 9. Ne2 ({Or} 9. Bd2 Nxb3 10. axb3
Bb7 11. Re1 O-O 12. Ne2 Nh5 13. c4 {This was Nunn, J - Kosten, A England 1998
Now Black had all the reasons to initiate an active play on the kingside by
means of} f5 $1 $15) 9... O-O 10. Ng3 Re8 11. Bd2 Nxb3 12. axb3 Bf8 $11 {
Tukhaev,A - Ragger, M Minsk 2015}) 7... O-O 8. h3 ({Allowing the pin with} 8.
O-O {doesn't seem appealing:} Bg4 9. Be3 (9. h3 Bxf3 10. Qxf3 Nd4 11. Qd1 b5 {
offers Black an excellent play either, but it was safer.}) 9... Nd4 10. Bxd4
exd4 11. Nb1 Nd7 12. Bb3 Ne5 13. Nbd2 Bh5 $36 {White was doomed to passive
defence in Abdusattorov,N - Khamdamov,S Dushanbe 2015}) 8... Nd4 {I like this
ambitious way of handling the position.} ({The solid} 8... Be6 $5 9. O-O b5 {
also should suffice for equality. For instance,} 10. Bb3 Bxb3 11. cxb3 h6 12.
Be3 {This was Nakar,E - Burke,J Philadelphia 2017 At this moment, Black should
have played} d5 $146 13. exd5 Nxd5 {, achieving good counterplay.}) 9. Nxd4
exd4 10. Ne2 d5 11. e5 $146 {Of course, this is the most challenging reply.} (
11. exd5 $6 Nxd5 12. O-O c5 13. Bb3 Be6 $15 {led White to a passive position
with a lack of space in Bartel, M - Shirov, A Prague CZE 2019}) 11... Nd7 12.
Bxd7 Bxd7 13. Nxd4 c5 14. Nf3 d4 15. O-O Bc6 {The space advantage and the
bishop pair provide Black with full compensation for the pawn.}) 6... b5 7. Bb3
d6 8. Nd5 {Among White's possibilities, this looks the most ambitious. White's
