1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. d3 b5 7. Bb3 O-O 8. a4
b4 9. Nbd2 {The most common choice. Since White's queen's knight has no other
prospects, it makes sense to start with this developing move.} (9. Bd5 {
with the idea to grab the e5 pawn but it isn't free of charge.} Nxd5 10. exd5
Nd4 11. Nxe5 {This was seen in a couple of games. I suggest the following way
of handling the position:} Bb7 {Black's unopposed light-squared bishop becomes
very powerful.} 12. c3 Nf5 13. cxb4 (13. c4 c6 14. Qg4 g6 15. dxc6 dxc6 $17)
13... Bxd5 14. Nc3 Bb7 15. Qg4 g6 {Black has excellent play for the pawn.}) (9.
Re1 {This rook move is often made with standard ideas. First, it makes the
d3-d4 advance more probable. Second, the f1-spot is now vacant for the knight.}
Bc5 {Again, Black activates the bishop before moving the d-pawn.} 10. Bg5 {
This pinning move was only tested in correspondence games.} (10. Nbd2 d6 11. h3
({After} 11. Nc4 Bg4 12. c3 Rb8 13. Rb1 h6 14. h3 Bh5 {Black was fine in
Linnichenko, M - Gaposhkin, N ICCF email 2012}) 11... h6 12. c3 Rb8 {As usual,
c2-c3 offers Black good prospects along the c-file.} 13. Nc4 Ba7 14. Be3 Bxe3
15. Nxe3 Na5 16. Bc2 Re8 17. Qd2 c5 {Black had a comfortable play in Polsterer,
H - Sabaev,S ICCF email 2014}) (10. c3 {This looks most consistent. White is
focused on seizing the centre.} bxc3 11. bxc3 Rb8 $1 {The Rb8 finds an
excellent job along the b-file.} 12. Bg5 (12. Nbd2 d6 13. h3 Ba7 14. Rb1 {
This was Petersons, I - Farias Magalhaes, F ICCF email 2012 Now Black could
have equalized by means of} h6 $146 15. Nf1 Be6 16. Be3 Bxe3 17. Nxe3 Qd7 $11)
({In case of} 12. d4 Ba7 {the lack of development in White's camp starts to
tell. In particular, after} 13. dxe5 $6 (13. Bg5 h6 14. Bh4 g5 15. Bg3 d6 16.
Bd5 Nxd5 17. exd5 Ne7 {was great for Black in Bernal Caamano, J - Uberos
Fernandez, A ICCF email 2008}) 13... Ng4 14. Ra2 Ngxe5 $15 {Black takes over
the initiative.}) 12... h6 13. Bh4 g5 14. Bg3 Nh5 $1 {This invites interesting
tactical complications.} 15. Nbd2 ({The main tactical point of Black's brave
play is} 15. Nxe5 Nxg3 16. Nxc6 dxc6 17. hxg3 Rxb3 $1 18. Qxb3 Qxd3 19. Qd1
Qxg3 20. Qf3 Qxf3 21. gxf3 Rd8 $36 {The powerful bishops provide Black full
compensation for the exchange.}) 15... Nxg3 16. hxg3 Qf6 {Black's pressure
along the a7-g1 diagonal is obvious now.} 17. Nc4 d6 18. Ne3 {We have been
following Carlsen, M - Aronian, L Karlsruhe/Baden-Baden 2017 At this moment
Black could have solved all the problems with} Bxe3 19. Rxe3 Na5 20. Ba2 Be6
$11) 10... d6 11. Nbd2 h6 12. Bh4 g5 13. Bg3 ({In case of} 13. Nxg5 hxg5 14.
Bxg5 {Black can release the tension by means of} Bg4 $1 15. Bxf6 Bxf2+ 16. Kxf2
Qxf6+ 17. Nf3 Nd4 {, seizing the initiative.}) 13... Rb8 {A decent
prophylactic move. Black's king is somewhat exposed, but it is compensated by
the poor location of the Bg3.} 14. c3 Ba7 15. a5 ({I've also examined} 15. Nf1
bxc3 16. bxc3 Nh5 17. Ne3 Nxg3 18. hxg3 Bxe3 19. Rxe3 Kg7 20. d4 Qf6 {White's
centre is under strong pressure, so Black faces no problems.}) 15... Be6 {
The position was balanced in Granski, M - Lafarga Santorroman, D ICCF email
2012}) 9... Bc5 {The position is closed, so Black affords moving the bishop
again in order to activate it.} (9... d6 {Is the most popular alternative.})
10. Nc4 (10. h3 d6 {This position was tested a few times on the highest level
and was proved to be comfortable for Black.} 11. c3 (11. Nc4 h6 12. c3 ({
Equally harmless is} 12. Be3 Bxe3 13. Nxe3 Be6 {Swiercz,D - Efimenko,Z Lublin
2012}) 12... Rb8 13. a5 bxc3 14. bxc3 Be6 {Black didn't face any problems in
Safarli, E - Eljanov,P Shamkir 2014}) (11. Re1 {transposes to 9.Re1}) 11... Rb8
12. Re1 Be6 13. a5 bxc3 14. bxc3 Bxb3 15. Nxb3 Ba7 16. Bg5 h6 17. Bxf6 ({
