1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3
O-O 9. d3 {This somewhat modest way of handling the position is known since
1905. Instead of 9.h3, followed by d2-d4 or the immediate 9.d4, White delays
the thematic advance till he transfers his knight to g3. As the practice
proves, Black mostly manages to exploit this loss of tempo (mostly White
shouldn't play d3-d4 when his Nf3 can be pinned, so he has to play h2-h3
anyway).} Na5 {Like in the Classical Chigorin system, White's bishop is
deprived of the a2-g8 diagonal, and now Black can advance his c-pawn and take
more control over the centre.} ({Switching to Breyer paths with} 9... Nb8 {
makes little sense now, since after} 10. Nbd2 Nbd7 11. Nf1 Nc5 12. Bc2 Bb7 13.
Ng3 Re8 14. d4 Ncd7 15. a4 Bf8 16. Bd3 $14 {White saves a tempo by not playing
h2-h3.}) 10. Bc2 c5 11. Nbd2 ({The immediate} 11. d4 {runs into} cxd4 12. cxd4
Bg4 $1 {Of course! Now White cannot maintain the tension in the centre.} 13.
dxe5 (13. d5 Qc7 $146 {This is the most flexible way of handling the position.
Now c8 is vacant for the king's rook as well.} ({Worse is} 13... Rc8 14. Nbd2
Nc4 15. Nxc4 bxc4 16. h3 {Yudasin, L - Almeida Saenz, A New Jersey 2008}) 14.
Nbd2 Rfc8 15. Bd3 Nb7 16. h3 Nc5 17. Bb1 Bh5 18. Nf1 Bg6 19. Ng3 Qd8 {Black
reached a harmonious setup and now has great prospects on the queenside.})
13... dxe5 14. Qxd8 Rfxd8 15. Nxe5 {White wins the central pawn, but leaving
the queenside pieces on their initial spots is a high price...} Rac8 16. Nc3
Be6 $1 $146 ({Worse is} 16... b4 $6 17. Nd5 {Kristjansson,S - Fivelstad,J
Reykjavik 2015}) 17. a3 {This waste of tempo is necessary.} Bd6 18. Nf3 Ng4 {
Now all Black's pieces are active.} 19. Bg5 f6 20. Bh4 Ne5 21. Bg3 Nxf3+ 22.
gxf3 Be7 {Black has full compensation for the pawn.}) (11. h3 Nc6 12. Nbd2 Re8
13. Nf1 {transposes to 11.Nbd2}) 11... Nc6 12. Nf1 Re8 {The most flexible. The
dark-squared bishop would be hosted on f8, so Black is getting ready for d3-d4
in advance.} 13. Ng3 ({White can hardly benefit from leaving the knight on f1:
} 13. h3 h6 14. d4 ({After} 14. a4 Be6 15. Ne3 b4 16. Bb3 Rb8 17. Bc4 Qc8 18.
Nh2 bxc3 19. bxc3 Na5 {Black had plenty of counter-play along the b-file in
