1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. a4 {
This aggressive move was first employed in the middle of the 20th century by
the great Pillsbury. Black's setup is somewhat exposed by b7-b5, so this
definitely looks challenging.} Bg4 {The most common. This pinning move makes
the d2-d4 advance more problematic. On the flipside, the bishop might
sometimes be misplaced on the h5-d1 diagonal.} ({There are few natural
alternatives like} 8... b4) (8... Bb7) ({or} 8... Bd7) 9. c3 {It's necessary
to cover d4.} O-O 10. h3 ({Another common continuation is} 10. d3 {, but
mostly White would play h2-h3 anyways, so it should transpose} Na5 {As in the
main line, now White has a choice.} 11. Bc2 (11. Ba2 b4 12. Nbd2 (12. cxb4 $6
Nc6 $15) 12... Rb8 13. h3 (13. Nc4 Nxc4 14. Bxc4 {, as in Zapata,A - Van der
Sterren,P Wijk aan Zee 1995 should be met by} c6 $1 {, and if} 15. Bxa6 Qa5 16.
Bc4 d5 {, then Black seizes the initiative.}) (13. d4 b3 $1 14. Bb1 (14. Nxb3
Nxb3 15. Bxb3 Bxf3 16. gxf3 Nh5 {is good for Black, similarly to the main line
- the presence of h-pawn instead of h3 doesn't change much.}) 14... c5 15. h3
Bh5 {tranpsposes to main line again.}) 13... Bh5 {transposes to 10.h3}) 11...
b4 12. Nbd2 Rb8 13. d4 (13. h3 Bh5) 13... bxc3 14. bxc3 exd4 $1 {The same
concept as in the main line - Black's pieces are better developed, so it makes
sense to open the position.} 15. cxd4 c5 16. dxc5 (16. h3 Bh5 {transposes to
10.h3 again}) ({Not much is neither offered by} 16. Ba3 cxd4 17. h3 Bh5 18. g4
Bg6 19. Nxd4 Re8 20. Nf5 Bxf5 21. exf5 d5 $132) 16... dxc5 17. Qe2 {White
improves the location of his queen and attacks the a6 pawn, but Black isn't
obliged to defend...} Nc6 $1 18. Qxa6 Nb4 19. Qc4 Be6 20. Qc3 c4 21. Ba3 Bc5 {
The active piece play supports the powerful c-passer. Black has full
compensation for a pawn.}) 10... Bh5 {In my opinion, this is the most
principled. True, the Bh5 is usually not so effective and can be potentially
attacked by White's queen's knight, but that would take a long time.} (10...
Bxf3 11. Qxf3 Na5 12. Bc2 b4 {is another common reaction, but the lack of the
light-squared bishop might pose Black definite problems in the long run.}) 11.
d3 ({The aggressive} 11. g4 Bg6 12. g5 {can be bravely met by} ({In case of} 
12. d3 Na5 13. Ba2 c5 14. axb5 axb5 15. Nh4 {White manages to liquidate the
light-squared bishop, but it takes a long time, so his bishop is getting
locked with} c4 16. Nxg6 hxg6 17. Nd2 {This was Salonen, J - Rajala, O ICCF
email 2006 Black should have played} Qc7 18. Bb1 Nd7 {, obtaining a good
position.}) 12... Nxe4 $1 ({Instead, the timid} 12... Nh5 13. Bd5 Qd7 14. d4 {
puts Black under definite pressure on the queenside.}) 13. Bd5 {The fork is
effective, but White's king is exposed.} Qd7 14. Bxe4 d5 $1 {This move forces
White to exchange the bishops in an unfavourable situation.} 15. Bxg6 fxg6 16.
Nxe5 Nxe5 17. Rxe5 Qxh3 18. Qf1 Qh4 19. Qg2 $2 {We have been following the
correspondence game Oestergaard, A - Daurelle, H IECG email 2000 Black could
have decided the game with} ({Better was} 19. d4 Qg4+ 20. Qg2 Qd1+ 21. Qf1 $11)
19... Bxg5 $1 20. Rxg5 Rae8 $19) 11... Na5 12. Bc2 {The most common retreat.} (
12. Ba2 {is also traditionally met by} b4 13. Nbd2 ({After} 13. cxb4 Nc6 14.
Bd2 Rb8 15. b5 axb5 16. axb5 Bxf3 17. Qxf3 Nd4 {The control over d4 offers
Black a comfortable play.}) (13. g4 b3 $1 14. Bxb3 Nxb3 15. Qxb3 Nxg4 16. hxg4
Bxg4 17. Nbd2 Rb8 18. Qc4 (18. Qc2 f5 19. Nh2 Qe8 20. exf5 Bxf5) 18... Qd7)
13... Rb8 14. d4 {At this moment Black can interrupt the coordination between
the opponent's pieces by means of} b3 $1 $146 ({Worse is} 14... c5 $6 {Keres,
P-Ragozin,V Parnu 1955} 15. g4 $1 Nxg4 (15... Bg6 16. dxe5 dxe5 17. Nxe5 $16)
16. hxg4 Bxg4 17. Bd5 bxc3 18. bxc3 Qc8 19. Nf1 $16 {Black doesn't have much
for the piece.}) 15. Nxb3 (15. Bb1 {makes the location of White's queenside
pieces rather awkward} c5 16. g4 {The most ambitious, but risky.} ({The quieter
} 16. Qe2 exd4 17. cxd4 Qc8 18. e5 dxe5 19. dxe5 Nd5 20. Ne4 Nb4 $132 {leads
