Na5 ({Or} 11... d5) 12. Bc2 c5 {, that frequently leads to complex struggle
a-la Benoni.} ({Or} 12... Nc4 13. Bc1 c5)) 11. h3 {The most common. White
covers g4, so the placement of the Be3 is secured.} ({The other natural
continuation} 11. Nbd2 {can be met by thematic break} d5 12. Qc1 {This
somewhat artificial move took place in a few high-level games.} (12. Bg5 exd4
13. exd5 ({I've also examined} 13. e5 $146 Ne4 14. Bxe7 Nxe7 15. cxd4 Ng5)
13... dxc3 14. dxc6 ({Harmless is} 14. bxc3 Na5 15. Re5 Bd6 16. Bxf6 Bxf3 17.
Qxf3 Qxf6 18. Qxf6 gxf6 {, and Black equalizes, to say the least.}) 14... cxd2
15. Qxd2 Qxd2 16. Bxd2 Bd6 17. Nh4 Rad8 18. Bc3 {Ponomariov,R - Svidler,P
Khanty-Mansiysk 2017} Rfe8 19. f3 ({After} 19. Nf5 Bc5 {Black doesn't face any
problems.}) 19... Kf8 20. g4 Bg6 21. Nxg6+ hxg6 $11 {The activity of pieces
fully compensates for White's bishop pair.}) (12. exd5 {By releasing the
tension in the centre White fails to pose Black any problems:} Nxd5 13. dxe5
Nxe5 14. Bd4 Nc6 15. Ne4 Nf4 $1 {The most energetic} 16. Ng3 Bg6 17. Be3 Nd3
18. Re2 Na5 19. Rd2 Nc4 20. Bxc4 bxc4 {Black had no problems due to the strong
Nd3 in Nisipeanu, L - Gyimesi, Z Germany 2004}) 12... dxe4 $5 $146 {I was
surprised to discover, that this natural continuation is a novelty.} ({One of
the merits behind White's last move is well illustrated in the following case:
} 12... exd4 13. cxd4 Nb4 14. e5 Ne4 15. a3 $1 Nd3 16. Qc6 Nxd2 17. Nxd2 Nxe1
18. Rxe1 {White had promising compensation for the exchange in Svetushkin, D -
Gledura,B Corund 2017}) 13. Nxe5 Nxe5 14. dxe5 Nd7 {The e4 pawn should fall
but Black is ready to recapture on e5. Now White is at crossroads:} 15. e6 {
The most ambitious choice. White manages to damage the opponent's king
structure, but it takes few tempi.} (15. Nxe4 Nxe5 16. Bc2 Re8 ({But not} 16...
Nd3 $2 17. Bxd3 Qxd3 18. Bd4 $16 {, and Black lacks harmony.}) 17. Bd4 ({
Equally harmless is} 17. Bf4 Nc4 18. a4 Bg6 19. Rd1 Qc8 $11) 17... Nc6 18. Bc5
Bg6 19. Rd1 Qc8 $11) 15... Ne5 $1 {Of course, the knight is heading to d3.} 16.
exf7+ (16. Nxe4 $6 Nd3 17. Qc2 Nxe1 18. Rxe1 Bg6 $15) 16... Kh8 17. Qc2 Nd3 18.
Rf1 ({In case of} 18. Red1 c5 ({Instead, the ''greedy''} 18... Bxd1 $2 19. Rxd1
c5 20. c4 {allows White to seize the initiative.}) 19. c4 Bg6 $1 $17 {White is
practically paralyzed by the monster Nd3.}) 18... Bg6 19. f3 exf3 20. Nxf3 c5
$1 {The strong Nd3 heavily restricts White's forces and yields Black full
compensation for the pawn.}) ({The relatively rare} 11. a4 {deserves attention:
} b4 {This is the most viable reaction: Black leaves the a-file locked and
seizes some space.} 12. Nbd2 (12. d5 Na5 13. Bc2 {is well met by} c5 $1 ({
But not} 13... b3 14. Bd3 c5 15. dxc6 Qc7 16. Nbd2 Qxc6 17. Bg5 $16 {Bartel,M
- Iovcov,V Reykjavik 2015}) 14. cxb4 cxb4 15. Nbd2 Ng4 16. Qe2 Nxe3 17. Qxe3
Qd7 {Black's chances are by no means worse.}) 12... bxc3 13. bxc3 exd4 14. cxd4
{This is the most natural recapture. However, it yields Black a stable spot on
b4.} (14. Bxd4 Na5 15. Ba2 ({Not much is offered by} 15. e5 dxe5 16. Bxe5 Nxb3
17. Qxb3 Re8 $11) 15... Nd7 16. e5 {This ambitious move actually invites
simplifications.} ({Hardly strong is} 16. Qc2 Re8 17. Rab1 c5 18. Be3 Bg6 19.
Bf4 Nb6 $132 {with mutual chances.}) 16... c5 17. exd6 Bxd6 18. Be3 Qc7 {
Black had a decent play in Sutovsky,E - Matlakov,M Jerusalem 2015}) 14... Nb4
15. h3 d5 16. e5 Ne4 17. g4 $2 {An over-optimistic decision.} ({Better was} 17.
Bc2 Nc3 18. Qc1 Nxc2 19. Qxc2 Bb4 {, but even then Black is doing well.}) 17...
Bg6 18. Nxe4 dxe4 19. Nd2 Nd3 {White got under strong pressure in Bajarani, U
- Iordachescu, V Abu Dhabi 2014}) 11... exd4 12. cxd4 Na5 {Similary to
above-mentioned note, Black deprives the bishop of the a2-g8 diagonal and
unlocks the c-pawn, that can challenge the pawn centre.} 13. Bc2 Nc4 (13... c5
{is perfectly playable, too, but the text seems most ambitious.}) 14. Bc1 {
White's current setup looks somewhat artificial - most of his pieces are
located on their initial spots. However, if nothing happens White would
quickly activate them.} d5 $1 {It turns out, that Black can take advantage of
his active minor pieces at once!} 15. e5 {This is the only adequate attempt to
fight for initiative.} ({After} 15. Nc3 dxe4 16. Nxe4 Bb4 $1 17. Nxf6+ Qxf6 18.
Re2 Bxf3 19. Qd3 g6 20. Qxf3 Qxf3 21. gxf3 Rfe8 $15 {White was struggling for
a draw in Purynychev, Y - Lukasevicius, P ICCF email 2013}) 15... Ne4 16. b3 {
This natural move isn't without drawbacks - it exposes c3.} ({After} 16. Nc3 {
White manages to exchange one of the powerful Black's knights, but now there
are clear targets in his camp on the queenside.} Nxc3 17. bxc3 a5 $1 {A
multi-purpose move. Apart from advancing his pawns, Black also yields an
opportunity of activating the rook via the 6th rank.} 18. Bf5 (18. g4 $6 Bg6
19. Bf5 b4 {was clearly better for Black in Wertjanz, D - Dragnev, V Graz 2017}
) 18... Ra6 19. Qd3 Bg6 {Black's setup is very solid now.} 20. Nd2 Bxf5 21.
Qxf5 Rc6 {White was struggling for equality in Lovakovic, F - Baranowski, T
LSS email 2011}) ({In case of} 16. Bxe4 $6 dxe4 17. Rxe4 f6 $1 {Black's lead
in development is getting threatening. The play might continue:} 18. e6 c5 19.
d5 Nb6 20. Nc3 b4 $17 {White's position was very close to a total collapse in
Wallace, J - Heimann, A Biel 2015}) 16... Nb6 17. Qd3 {White managed to avoid
the nasty pin, but he still desperately lacks harmony.} ({Like earlier, the
materialistic approach isn't appealing:} 17. Bxe4 dxe4 18. Rxe4 Nd5 19. Bb2 f5
20. Re1 {This was Eliseev,U - Matlakov,M Kolomna 2016 Now the energetic} Nf4 $1
21. Nc3 b4 22. Na4 Qd5 $36 {would have yielded Black a dangerous initiative.})
17... Bg6 18. Qe2 Rc8 $1 {This precise move enables Black to develop his
initiative.} ({Instead,} 18... c5 19. Nbd2 Nxd2 20. Qxd2 {was unclear in Xiong,
J - Homa, S Saint Louis 2013}) 19. Nbd2 Bb4 20. a3 Bc3 21. Ra2 c5 $36 {White's
problems are undeniable.} *

